00:27:08.880 --> 00:27:09.980
ROMAN NURIK: As engineers.

00:27:09.980 --> 00:27:11.680
ALEX FAABORG: What sort of
feeling you want to evoke and

00:27:11.680 --> 00:27:13.140
what you're trying to
communicate with the graphics.

00:27:13.140 --> 00:27:17.750
But flows are also really useful
for just understanding

00:27:17.750 --> 00:27:20.480
the temporal complexity
of your application.

00:27:20.480 --> 00:27:21.980
Which, it's important
to get it up on the

00:27:21.980 --> 00:27:22.700
board and look at it.

00:27:22.700 --> 00:27:26.070
And saying is it actually too
difficult to get from this

00:27:26.070 --> 00:27:27.170
location to this
other location?

00:27:27.170 --> 00:27:28.345
There's too many navigation
steps.

00:27:28.345 --> 00:27:31.150
It's going to take the
user too much time.

00:27:31.150 --> 00:27:33.660
People often think about
complexity in terms of the

00:27:33.660 --> 00:27:35.730
number of objects on screen.

00:27:35.730 --> 00:27:39.430
But if you make things simpler
by introducing navigational

00:27:39.430 --> 00:27:41.680
steps, you've really just kind
of shifted your complexity

00:27:41.680 --> 00:27:43.080
into a different type
of complexity.

00:27:43.080 --> 00:27:47.050
So it's really good to look at
the sequences so you can see

00:27:47.050 --> 00:27:49.960
temporal complexity.

